{# "Bulletproof" table-based button - the standard email-safe pattern. Everything stays inline (Outlook strips
   most <style> rules and ignores CSS on <table>/<td> unless it's already inline) - including background-color/color,
   so the button still renders correctly in _wrapper.html.twig's standalone fallback (no EmailLayoutProviderInterface
   registered, so nothing inlines its <style> block for us). "btn"/"btn-primary" are also kept as classes so a real
   theme (wrapped through EmailLayoutProviderInterface, e.g. SiteBundle's own CSS inliner) can still override these
   defaults with its own brand color. "border-spacing:0;margin:0" on the inner table blocks the site's generic
   "table{border-spacing:10px;margin:0 auto 1em auto}" rule from adding unwanted gaps around the button;
   align="center" replaces that same rule's auto-centering (HTML attribute, not CSS - Outlook-safe); "box-shadow:none"
   is set inline to override ".btn"'s own theme box-shadow, which reads badly on a small bulletproof button #}
<tr>
    <td style="padding:0 24px 24px;text-align:center;">
        <table role="presentation" align="center" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0" style="border-spacing:0;margin:0 auto;">
            <tr>
                <td class="btn-primary" style="border-radius:4px;background-color:#2563eb;">
                    <a href="{{ url }}" target="_blank" class="btn" style="display:inline-block;padding:12px 28px;font-size:15px;font-weight:bold;color:#ffffff;text-decoration:none;border-radius:4px;box-shadow:none;">{{ label }}</a>
                </td>
            </tr>
        </table>
    </td>
</tr>
